    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "c80c64cf"
      },
      "source": [
        "## Lambda functions with pandas `assign`\n",
        "\n",
        "The `assign()` method in Pandas is a convenient way to create new columns for a DataFrame. It returns a *new* DataFrame with the new columns added, rather than modifying the original DataFrame in place (though you can reassign the result back to the original variable).\n",
        "\n",
        "The `assign()` method is particularly useful with lambda functions because it allows you to define new columns based on the DataFrame's existing columns in a clean and readable way. The lambda function passed to `assign` takes the entire DataFrame as its argument, making it easy to reference other columns.\n",
        "\n",
        "The basic syntax is `df.assign(new_col_name=lambda x: expression_using_x)`. Here, `x` represents the DataFrame itself within the lambda function's scope. You can assign multiple new columns by providing multiple keyword arguments to `assign`."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 224
        },
        "id": "6113acd0",
        "outputId": "03ecbbeb-0fc5-49de-b333-323e30659afe"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Use assign with lambda functions to create new columns\n",
        "# Create a column 'product_col1_col3' which is the product of 'col1' and 'col3'\n",
        "# Create a column 'col1_is_large' which is True if 'col1' > 30, False otherwise\n",
        "df_assigned = df.assign(\n",
        "    product_col1_col3=lambda x: x['col1'] * x['col3'],\n",
        "    col1_is_large=lambda x: x['col1'] > 30\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Display the DataFrame with the newly created columns\n",
